Background
A coordinated attack against the Estuary North Bank of Dufftown. Clients were reporting failed payments and missing funds, 
while IT was seeing failures in the Core Banking System. The goal was to figure out what happened, whether it was still ongoing, and how it was done.
We had two resources: an ELK stack aggregating logs from across the environment, and SSH access to the Core Banking Server.

Investigation
Getting Oriented on the Server
First thing I did was SSH in and look around. Started in /home/admin1 — nothing interesting, just standard dot files. Moved up to the root of the filesystem:
bashls -la /
Spotted message.txt sitting in / — not a file that belongs there. Opened it:
bashcat /message.txt
Ransom note. Confirmed this was ransomware. Grabbed the attacker's contact email and noted the Bitcoin payment demand.

Finding the ATM Logs
Knew ATM logs were involved based on the brief, so went looking:
bashsudo find / -name "*.enc" -o -name "*atm*" 2>/dev/null
Found /var/log/ATMs/ containing several encrypted files and one surviving readable log:
bashls -lah /var/log/ATMs/
-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 301K Sep 12 09:58 07-04--17-28-11.log
-rw-r--r-- 1 root root  28K Sep 12 08:21 07-04--17-28-11.log.enc
-rw-r--r-- 1 root root  13K Sep 12 08:21 17-08--15-17-31.log.enc
-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 9.4K Sep 12 08:21 17-08--15-30-54.log.enc
-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 6.6K Sep 12 08:21 17-08--16-08-04.log.enc
-rw-r--r-- 1 root root  13K Sep 12 08:21 17-08--16-18-01.log.enc
All .enc files share the same timestamp — 08:21 — meaning the ransomware hit everything at once. 
One log survived unencrypted, which became useful for reading post-compromise activity.
To narrow down what else happened in that window:
bashfind / -type f -newermt "2021-09-12 08:15:00" ! -newermt "2021-09-12 08:25:00" 2>/dev/null
This confirmed the /message.txt drop and all .enc files appeared within the same narrow timeframe.

Pivoting to ELK
Switched over to Kibana to look at what the ATMs were doing. 
Used the Filebeat index (core banking and Linux logs) with the time range covering the incident period.
Searching for traffic from the ATM IPs revealed a clear pattern of ATM-to-Core-Banking communication. 
Also found large unauthorized withdrawal requests being processed shortly after the 08:21 encryption event — 
confirming the attack had a financial fraud component running alongside the ransomware.
Checked the Winlogbeat index for Windows-side activity and found ATM machine accounts (ATM-1$) 
authenticating to the Domain Controller around the same timeframe, suggesting credential abuse or lateral movement was part of the chain.

